{"type":"message","id":"50332477","parentId":"6f2292b9","timestamp":"2026-05-14T10:07:01.309Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `Assets\\Scripts\\Modules\\GASDK\\` folder has miscellaneous GASDK-related scripts but NOT the `GiantSDK` wrapper files. The wrapper source files are in `OtherPlugins\\GASDK\\GiantSDK\\`. \n\nThese wrapper files define the `GiantSDK.Parent` namespace and provide stubs/interfaces for the GiantSDK API. They need to be in a place where the Unity compiler can find them when `GASDK` define is active.\n\nThe correct approach is to copy `OtherPlugins\\GASDK\\GiantSDK\\*` into a location in Assets. The most logical place would be `Assets\\Scripts\\Modules\\GASDK\\GiantSDK\\` or `Assets\\Plugins\\GiantSDK\\`.\n\nLet me just copy them to `Assets\\Plugins\\GiantSDK\\` since that would make them available globally.\n\nWait, actually, before I do that - let me check if the SDK plan is supposed to handle this. The `GuanFangPC` plan uses `GUANFANGPC` define and has no special files. For Standalone (PC) builds, none of the plans seem to include the GiantSDK source code into Assets.\n\nLet me look at what the OtherPlugins/GASDK folder is for. It might be that these files are intentionally placed outside Assets and should be linked or symlinked.\n\nActually, I think the issue might be simpler - the GASDK define was inadvertently left in the scripting define symbols. For hot update builds (which just build asset bundles), we shouldn't need the GASDK define at all. Let me look at the pipeline configuration to see what it expects.\n\nYou know what, let me just go ahead and copy the GiantSDK wrapper files to Assets. That's the least invasive fix and will make the project compile properly.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"Let me copy the GiantSDK wrapper source files into Assets so Unity can compile them."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_fUp8ByTIJZafbgU9XLtH1451","name":"exec","arguments