{"type":"message","id":"5e67fa09","parentId":"77d566fa","timestamp":"2026-05-14T10:08:10.718Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"There's an `AOT.asmdef` in `Assets\\AOTRunTime\\Scripts\\AOT.asmdef`. And there are also many asmdef files in the `Plugins` folder. The GiantSDK files I copied to `Assets\\Plugins\\GiantSDK\\` don't have an asmdef file, so they'd be compiled into the default assembly. But the AOTRunTime scripts reference `GiantSDK.Parent`, and AOTRunTime has its own assembly definition (`AOT.asmdef`).\n\nIf `AOT.asmdef` doesn't reference the default assembly (where the GiantSDK source files would be), the AOTRunTime scripts can't use `GiantSDK.Parent`.\n\nLet me check the AOT.asmdef.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_ADLVSdZvGmbMRwvY3ugl3280","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"E:\\Solo\\nightoffullmoon\\client\\cardv\\Assets\\AOTRunTime\\Scripts\\AOT.asmdef"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":1726,"output":243,"cacheRead":55936,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":57905,"cost":{"input":0.00024164000000000002,"output":0.00006804,"cacheRead":0.001566208,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.001875888}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778753287919,"responseId":"0f78d58a-ca35-4e44-82b8-8dc5480f4e81"}}
{"type":"message","id":"8345eebb","parentId":"5e67fa09","timestamp":"2026-05-14T10:08:10.748Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_00_ADLVSdZvGmbMRwvY3ugl3280","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\r\n    \"name\": \"AOT\",\r\n    \"rootNamespace\": \"\",\r\n    \"references\": [\r\n        \"GUID:13ba8ce62aa80c74598530029cb2d649\",\r\n        \"GUID:e34a5702dd353724aa315fb8011f08c3\",\r\n        \"GUID:f22fac247a56d2d41b687bb0d900e54e\",\r\n        \"GUID:c55575a9f1747c240822f4b7e0400716\",\r\n        \"GUID:b35e33884f6755d43b7e0511e88956d0\",\r\n        \"GUID:1ea6b676786131e4095182b742bb64ec\",\r\n        \"GUID:e4846172d739f524aae9f861611f3bed\",\r\n        \"GUID:cbc17d0cd4c154740aa2cb49ae39da9b\",\r\n        \"GUID:f06555f75b070af458a003d92f9efb00\"\r\n    ],\r\n    \"includePlatforms\": [],\r\n    \"excludePlatforms\": [],\r\n    \"allowUnsafeCode\": false,\r\n    \"overrideReferences\": false,\r\n    \"precompiledReferences\": [],\r\n    \"autoReferenced\": true,\r\n    \"defineConstraints\": [],\r\n    \"versionDefines\": [],\r\n    \"noEngineReferences\": false\r\n}"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1778753290748}}
{"type":"message","id":"5fc3152f","parentId":"8345eebb","timestamp":"2026-05-14T10:08:18.368Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `AOT.asmdef` has specific references to other assemblies (by GUID). It doesn't reference the default assembly. Since the GiantSDK source files I copied to `Assets\\Plugins\\GiantSDK\\` don't have an asmdef, they'd be compiled into the default \"Assembly-CSharp\" assembly (or maybe not if they're in a specific folder that gets its own assembly).\n\nWait, in Unity 2020, scripts in the `Plugins` folder without an asmdef file are compiled into a special Assembly-CSharp-firstpass or Assembly-Plugins assembly. Since the AOT assembly explicitly references certain assemblies but likely doesn't reference the Plugins assembly, that would explain why `GiantSDK.Parent` can't be found by the AOT scripts.\n\nActually, looking more carefully - the `AOT.asmdef` references use GUIDs. If the AOT assembly doesn't have a reference to the default assembly (Assembly-CSharp), it won't be able to access types from it.\n\nThe issue is that I put the GiantSDK files in `Assets\\Plugins\\GiantSDK\\`. In Unity without an asmdef, scripts in `Plugins` are compiled into `Assembly-CSharp-firstpass` or something similar. Meanwhile, the `AOT.asmdef` assembly needs explicit references to access types from other assemblies.\n\nThe best fix would be to either:\n1. Add an asmdef to `Assets\\Plugins\\GiantSDK\\` and add a reference to it from AOT.asmdef\n2. OR put the files in a location that's compiled into the default assembly\n3. OR use `#if` guards properly to only compile the using directive when the SDK DLL is actually present\n\nActually, looking at the code again:\n```csharp\n#if GASDK || STEAMGIANT || WeGame || GUANFANGPC\nusing GiantSDK.Parent;\n#endif\n```\n\nThe conditional compilation should prevent the `using` from being evaluated when none of these defines are set. But the `GASDK` define IS set in the project settings!\n\nLet me think about this differently. The `GASDK` define is being set by the project's scripting defines. The plugin is expected to be there as well. It's a configuration issue - either:\n1. Remove GASDK from Standalone defines\n2. Or make the GiantSDK plugin available\n\nThe quickest solution is option 1 - remove GASDK from the Standalone scripting defines. Since this is a hot update pipeline (building asset bundles for test server), it doesn't need the GASDK plugin.\n\nLet me check if there's a tool to modify the scripting defines, or if I should just modify the ProjectSettings.asset file directly.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"The asmdef architecture is preventing the AOT assembly from seeing the GiantSDK plugin. The simplest fix is to remove the `GASDK` define from Standalone platform since this is a hot update pipeline (doesn't need it)."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_i8rbjD3uR6MKPDLds49t0825","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"E:\\Solo\\nightoffullmoon\\client\\cardv\\ProjectSettings\\ProjectSettings.asset","offset":631,"limit":10}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":403,"output":729,"cacheRead":57856,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":58988,"cost":{"input":0.000056420000000000005,"output":0.00020412000000000002,"cacheRead":0.001619968,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0018805080000000001}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778753290749,"responseId":"147d8e4a-0c5d-403a-af01-e4e687056cf8"}}
{"type":"message","id":"b23cd525","parentId":"5fc3152f","timestamp":"2026-05-14T10:08:18.395Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_00_i8rbjD3uR6MKPDLds49t0825","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"  webGLThreadsSupport: 0\n  webGLDecompressionFallback: 0\n  scriptingDefineSymbols:\n    1: UNITY_POST_PROCESSING_STACK_V2;AMPLIFY_SHADER_EDITOR;TextMeshPro;GASDK;GuanFang;CRASH_SIGHT;PerfSight\n    4: TextMeshPro;GASDK;GuanFang;CRASH_SIGHT;PerfSight\n    7: UNITY_POST_PROCESSING_STACK_V2;AMPLIFY_SHADER_EDITOR;ENABLE_HYBRIDCLR;ENABLE_ERROR_AND_ABOVE_LOG;GM_COMMOND;TESTIN;LOGGER_ON;ALLLOG;TESTRATE;ENABLE_LOG;HOTFIX_ENABLE;GASDK;GuanFang;CRASH_SIGHT;PerfSight;TextMeshPro\n    13: UNITY_POST_PROCESSING_STACK_V2;TextMeshPro\n    14: UNITY_POST_PROCESSING_STACK_V2;TextMeshPro\n    19: UNITY_POST_PROCESSING_STACK_V2;TextMeshPro\n    21: UNITY_POST_PROCESSING_STACK_V2;TextMeshPro\n\n[113 more lines in file. Use offset=641 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1778753298395}}
{"type":"message","id":"ff26ea82","parentId":"b23cd525","timestamp":"2026-05-14T10:08:27.875Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Looking at the scripting define symbols:\n- Platform 1: Standalone (Windows/Mac/Linux) - has GASDK\n- Platform 4: Android - has GASDK  \n- Platform 7: Android (something specific) - has GASDK\n- Platform 13: iOS (probably) - no GASDK\n- Platform 14: iOS (arm64) - no GASDK\n- Platform 19: WebGL - no GASDK\n- Platform 21: Xbox/other - no GASDK\n\nFor hot update, we're running on Standalone (platform 1). The GASDK define is causing the compilation errors. The hot update pipeline doesn't need GASDK at all.\n\nHowever, I shouldn't permanently modify the project settings. Instead, let me try a different approach:\n\n1. Copy the GiantSDK files to a location that's compiled into the default assembly (not Plugins) - like `Assets/Scripts/GiantSDK/`\n2. Or create an asmdef that the AOT assembly can reference\n\nWait, actually let me think about this more. The `Assets\\Plugins` folder scripts WITHOUT asmdef files are compiled into `Assembly-CSharp-firstpass` or the default assembly depending on the Unity version. In Unity 2020.3:\n\nActually, let me look at the other approach - in the `AOT.asmdef` references, maybe I should find where the other SDK references come from. Or better yet, let me just add an asmdef to the GiantSDK folder and reference it from AOT.asmdef.\n\nActually, the simplest approach: move the GiantSDK files OUT of Plugins and into somewhere that's in the default assembly, like `Assets\\AOTRunTime\\Scripts\\GiantSDK\\`. Then they'd be compiled into the AOT assembly or the default assembly if they're outside the AOT folder... wait, that won't work either because asmdef boundaries.\n\nActually, a much simpler approach: just add an asmdef file to the GiantSDK folder and reference its GUID from AOT.asmdef. Let me first check what the GUID would be.\n\nActually, let me take the simplest possible approach and just move the files to a folder without an asmdef that the AOT assembly references, OR add the asmdef reference.\n\nWait. The error is `The type or namespace name 'GiantSDK' could not be found`. This means the `using GiantSDK.Parent;` can't resolve. If I put the GiantSDK files in a location compiled into the default assembly (like Assets/Scripts/GiantSDK without asmdef), the AOT assembly still can't see it because AOT.asmdef has explicit references and might not reference Assembly-CSharp.\n\nLet me check: does the AOT.asmdef have `\"autoReferenced\": true`? Yes it does. But `autoReferenced` means the assembly is auto-referenced by other assemblies, not that it auto-references others.\n\nHmm, actually in Unity 2019.4+, when you define an asmdef assembly, it does NOT automatically reference the default assembly. You have to explicitly add that reference.\n\nThe best approach is to add the GiantSDK files to a folder inside the AOT assembly's scope (i.e., inside `Assets/AOTRunTime/Scripts/`), or create a separate asmdef for GiantSDK and add it as a reference.\n\nOr the simplest approach: put the files directly in `Assets/AOTRunTime/Scripts/GiantSDK/` so they're part of the AOT assembly.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_BVSPo7gsLiLjclwig2Xd3326","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Copy-Item -Path \"E:\\Solo\\nightoffullmoon\\client\\cardv\\OtherPlugins\\GASDK\\GiantSDK\" -Destination \"E:\\Solo\\nightoffullmoon\\client\\cardv\\Assets\\AOTRunTime\\Scripts\\GiantSDK\" -Recurse -Force","timeout":10}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":410,"output":899,"cacheRead":58880,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":60189,"cost":{"input":0.000057400000000000006,"output":0.00025172000000000004,"cacheRead":0.00164864,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0019577600000000002}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778753298397,"responseId":"892639dc-7f5d-4f2c-81f5-ce24b5d8a69e"}}
