{"type":"message","id":"6238fe91","parentId":"361d6df9","timestamp":"2026-05-14T10:27:00.613Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see! The log shows:\n1. `Generate EventInterface Complete` - generated during initialization\n2. `===============Initialize BuildPipeline: Executing===============` - from `YYZY.BuildPipeline.BuildPipeline:.cctor()` (the static constructor)\n3. After that it's just asset importing\n\nThe problem is that `===============Initialize BuildPipeline: Executing===============` was printed by the static constructor `.cctor()` of the BuildPipeline class, not by the `RunHotUpdatePipeline` method itself. The static constructor runs during assembly loading, before the executeMethod is called.\n\nAfter the static constructor, Unity imported assets but the pipeline method itself never seems to have run. Unity exited (code 0) without ever calling `RunHotUpdatePipeline`.\n\nThis is a known Unity 2020 issue - `-executeMethod` might not properly execute if there's a long import that times out.\n\nActually wait, let me check the full log again. The process ran for about 20 minutes (from 18:03 to 18:26). The pipeline execution would happen AFTER imports complete. But imports only got to line 8102 (last line 6126... wait, the last content I saw from the log was around line 8102 but the total was much higher.\n\nActually the log has 8125+ lines and the tail showed it was still importing at line 8125. The process exited with code 0. This suggests Unity quit early while imports were still in progress.\n\nBut wait - the `-executeMethod` in Unity 2020 runs AFTER all initial imports complete. If Unity is quitting before imports finish, either:\n1. There was an error that caused Unity to quit\n2. The method ran but didn't produce any log output\n\nLet me check if maybe the pipeline method produced output to a different log or to a temp file. Actually, let me try a different approach - let me run the pipeline again but remove the `-quit` flag to see if it stays running longer. Or alternatively, let me check if there's a way to see the actual pipeline output.\n\nActually, looking at the exit code being 0 and the process having completed within the timeout, I think the most likely explanation is that Unity's `-executeMethod + -quit` combination didn't work as expected due to the massive import process.\n\nLet me try WITHOUT the `-quit` flag and with a longer timeout. The script execution should still work, and I can kill Unity manually after it completes.\n\nWait actually, without `-quit` Unity will keep running. The executeMethod will run after imports. But then Unity stays open.\n\nLet me try a different approach - use `-executeMethod` without `-quit` but with a timeout to kill Unity after a while.\n\nActually, the better approach is to look at this from a different angle. The current plan configuration is \"Undefined\" with no SDK plan applied. The hot update pipeline probably needs a specific SDK plan to be applied first, but we can't apply it because the scripts won't compile without the SDK files.\n\nLet me try running Unity again, this time without `-quit` and with a timeout, to make sure the pipeline actually gets to run.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_7ccmeISbqbKkNsnbO5gc8001","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"& \"C:\\Program Files\\Unity\\Hub\\Editor\\2020.3.49f1\\Editor\\Unity.exe\" -batchmode -nographics -projectPath \"E:\\Solo\\nightoffullmoon\\client\\cardv\" -buildTarget Win64 -executeMethod YYZY.BuildPipeline.BuildPipeline.RunHotUpdatePipeline -logFile \"E:\\Solo\\nightoffullmoon\\client\\cardv\\BuildPipeline_RunHotUpdate.log\"","timeout":10800,"yieldMs":600000}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":1036,"output":846,"cacheRead":108416,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":110298,"cost":{"input":0.00014504,"output":0.00023688000000000002,"cacheRead":0.0030356479999999997,"cacheWri