{"type":"message","id":"b5a56308","parentId":"cc097de2","timestamp":"2026-05-14T10:36:28.564Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, before running Unity again with a clean Library - that's going to take an extremely long time (hours!) to import everything from scratch. That's not practical.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The issue seems to be that Unity exits before calling the executeMethod. But the previous run with `-quit` actually got much further (8125 lines) than without `-quit` (3387 lines). That's strange.\n\nActually, looking at the first run more carefully - that was the run where we had the GASDK defines removed, and we got the script compilation to succeed. That run made it to 8125 lines of asset imports before exiting. \n\nThen when I re-ran without `-quit`, we only got to 3387 lines. This means the first run (with `-quit`) was importing -quit's first-run assets, and the second run should have been faster because assets were cached. But we deleted the cache!\n\nOh wait, no - the cache was deleted between the runs. The first run created the Library cache. Then I deleted it. The second run had to start from scratch and was killed early.\n\nActually, looking back at the timeline:\n1. First run (with -quit, BuildTarget Win64): got to 8125 lines, exited with code 0\n2. Then I deleted the Library folder completely\n\nSo now I've deleted the Library folder and we're back to square one - a completely clean import is needed.\n\nBut that will take way too long. Let me reconsider the approach.\n\nActually, let me try running the bat file with the correct UNITY_PATH. The issue was that the bat file had `2020.3.49f1c1` but the actual folder is `2020.3.49f1`. Let me update the bat file.\n\nBut more importantly, the bat file runs without `-buildTarget`, so it'll default to Android. And it has `-quit` which caused the pipeline to not run in the first run.\n\nActually wait - the first run DID get to 8125 lines. That's a lot of asset imports. The pipeline might have actually executed after all imports completed, but we just didn't see its output because it doesn't log to the same log file.\n\nLet me look at the first run's log more carefully. Can I find any trace of the pipeline method being called?\n\nActually, the log was overwritten by the second run. So I can't check the first run's log anymore.\n\nLet me think about what I know:\n1. The bat file runs Unity with `-batchmode -quit -nographics -projectPath ... -executeMethod YYZY.BuildPipeline.BuildPipeline.RunHotUpdatePipeline -logFile ...`\n2. Unity compiled successfully with GASDK removed from Standalone defines\n3. Asset imports started\n4. Unity exited with code 0\n\nThe pipeline method `RunHotUpdatePipeline` - if it runs after all imports are complete. But the log only shows imports. Maybe the pipeline method ran but printed to the Editor log (console) which is separate from the -logFile?\n\nActually, `-logFile` captures ALL Unity output, not just the console. So if the pipeline method printed to Debug.Log, it would show in the log file.\n\nUnless... the pipeline method is a static method that's called by Unity's executeMethod attribute. But in Unity, `-executeMethod` runs the method BEFORE the first frame (during the initial domain reload). Let me check if the method ran.\n\nLooking at the log again - line 33 shows the command line including the executeMethod: `YYZY.BuildPipeline.BuildPipeline.RunHotUpdatePipeline`. The static constructor `.cctor()` ran (line 236). But after that, it's all imports.\n\nMaybe the pipeline method was supposed to run but it aborted because the `RunHotUpdatePipeline` method calls `EditorApplication.Exit` or something similar.\n\nActually, I bet the problem is simpler than I think. The pipeline method has a `-quit` flag in the batch call. When the method finishes, Unity quits. But if the method runs immediately after static initialization (before imports), it might not be able to do its work properly.\n\nWait, in Unity, `-executeMethod` methods run AFTER all initial asset imports. The flow is:\n1. Start Unity\n2. Reload domain\n3. Complete all asset imports (first-time import or reimport)\n4. Call the executeMethod\n5. If -quit, exit\n\nSo the method should run after imports complete. But our log only shows imports with no trace of the method.\n\nUnless the method ran but produced no log output and immediately returned (because it couldn't find the configuration it needed).\n\nLet me check the BuildPipeline.cs file to see what RunHotUpdatePipeline does.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_w7ngi0JC0z8aOhfPpDJK5185","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Select-String -Path \"E:\\Solo\\nightoffullmoon\\client\\cardv\\Assets\\Editor\\BuildPipeline\\BuildPipeline.cs\" -Pattern \"RunHotUpdate\" -Context 0,15","timeout":5}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":30,"output":1104,"cacheRead":120704,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":121838,"cost":{"input":0.0000042000000000000004,"output":0.00030912,"cacheRead":0.003379712,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.003693032}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778754975756,"responseId":"211a2a49-7c3f-4164-9098-0fb843510172"}}
